<div id="review_3082141556" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3082141556" />
    <a title="Jennifer (Insert Lit Pun)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32647049-jennifer-insert-lit-pun"><img alt="Jennifer (Insert Lit Pun)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1596146753p2/32647049.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3082141556?book_show_action=true">Dec 31, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jennifer (Insert Lit Pun)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jennifer (Insert Lit Pun)" href="/user/show/32647049-jennifer-insert-lit-pun">Jennifer (Insert Lit Pun)</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3082141556" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer151278589619363081">There’s no way I would’ve finished this if Mantel weren’t one of my favorite authors. And even then, there was a whole lot of sunk cost fallacy getting me to the end. It’s fascinating to see the germination for her later (greater) novels by examining what does and doesn’t work in this one. For me, there was too much historical detail and unconventional structure, with too little novelistic glue to help the reader appreciate and enjoy these other elements. The Thomas Cromwell novels lead you down</span>
  <span id="freeText151278589619363081" style="display:none">There’s no way I would’ve finished this if Mantel weren’t one of my favorite authors. And even then, there was a whole lot of sunk cost fallacy getting me to the end. It’s fascinating to see the germination for her later (greater) novels by examining what does and doesn’t work in this one. For me, there was too much historical detail and unconventional structure, with too little novelistic glue to help the reader appreciate and enjoy these other elements. The Thomas Cromwell novels lead you down a dark stairwell with enough guidance and assuredness to make the murk thrilling. This novel leaves you to stumble down the stairwell—slick surface, no bannister, and you’re not even sure you’re going anywhere worthwhile. But there’s enough casual brilliance peppered throughout that I expect this would be a great read for people who are already intimately familiar (and I do mean intimately) with the French Revolution.</span>
  <a data-text-id="151278589619363081" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


